# Backend: Logging

## Format
- Use structured JSON logging in all environments
- Every log entry MUST include: `timestamp`, `level`, `correlationId`, `service`
- Add `operation`, `duration_ms`, and `status` for request-level logs
- Use ISO 8601 timestamps with timezone (`2026-01-15T10:30:00Z`)

## Log Levels
| Level | Use for |
|-------|---------|
| `error` | Unexpected failures requiring attention |
| `warn` | Recoverable issues or deprecation notices |
| `info` | Key business events (request start/end, state changes) |
| `debug` | Detailed diagnostic info (dev/staging only in high volume) |

- Default production level: `info`
- Never use `console.log` in production code; use the project logger

## PII Rules (CRITICAL)
- **NEVER** log: full names, emails, phone numbers, SSNs, credit card numbers, passwords
- **NEVER** log `req.body` or `res.body` — may contain PII or secrets
- Mask when necessary: `email: "j***@example.com"`, `phone: "***-***-1234"`
- Use only `userId`, `sessionId`, `correlationId` to identify users in logs

## Correlation
- Generate a `correlationId` (UUID v4) at the request boundary if not provided
- Propagate via `X-Correlation-Id` header across service calls
- Include in every log entry and error response

## Performance Logging
- Log request duration for all API endpoints
- Log slow queries (> 500ms) at `warn` level
- Use sampling for high-volume debug logs (e.g. 1 in 100)

## Anti-patterns
- Don't log inside tight loops — aggregate or sample
- Don't use string interpolation for log messages — use structured fields
- Don't log secrets, tokens, or API keys under any circumstances
- Don't use different logging libraries in the same project
